05066nam a22007335i 9780812204070DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20112006pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013937806  a97808122040707 a10.9783/97808122040702doi  a(DE-B1597)449334  a(OCoLC)979578136  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a659.19/664009731 aParkin, Katherine J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFood Is Love :bAdvertising and Gender Roles in Modern America /cKatherine J. Parkin. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b25 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 Advertisers and Their Paradigm: Women as Consumers -- tChapter 2 Love, Fear, and Freedom: Selling Traditional Gender Roles -- tChapter 3 Women’s Power to Make Us: Cooking Up a Family’s Identity -- tChapter 4 Authority and Entitlement: Men in Food Advertising -- tChapter 5 Health, Beauty, and Sexuality: A Woman’s Responsibility -- tChapter 6 A Mother’s Love: Children and Food Advertising -- tEpilogue -- tPeriodical and Archive Sources and Abbreviations -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aModern advertising has changed dramatically since the early twentieth century, but when it comes to food, Katherine Parkin writes, the message has remained consistent. Advertisers have historically promoted food in distinctly gendered terms, returning repeatedly to themes that associated shopping and cooking with women. Foremost among them was that, regardless of the actual work involved, women should serve food to demonstrate love for their families. In identifying shopping and cooking as an expression of love, ads helped to both establish and reinforce the belief that kitchen work was women's work, even as women's participation in the labor force dramatically increased. Alternately flattering her skills as a homemaker and preying on her insecurities, advertisers suggested that using their products would give a woman irresistible sexual allure, a happy marriage, and healthy children. Ads also promised that by buying and making the right foods, a woman could help her family achieve social status, maintain its racial or ethnic identity, and assimilate into the American mainstream.Advertisers clung tenaciously to this paradigm throughout great upheavals in the patterns of American work, diet, and gender roles. To discover why, Food Is Love draws on thousands of ads that appeared in the most popular magazines of the twentieth and early twenty-first centuries, including the Ladies' Home Journal, Good Housekeeping, Ebony, and the Saturday Evening Post. The book also cites the records of one of the nation's preeminent advertising firms, as well as the motivational research advertisers utilized to reach their customers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aHome Economics. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aHome Economics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package American Historyz978311041349608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220407040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812204070423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812204070/original  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041349-6  Penn Press eBo